mo></mrow></mfenced></math></p>\n<p><br><strong>Note:</strong> Accept equivalent forms, e.g. <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>L</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>t</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>06</mn><mo> </mo><mi>sin</mi><mo>(</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>00939</mn><mi>t</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>151</mn><mo>)</mo><mo>+</mo><mn>12</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></math>.<br>Follow through on their answer to part (g) replacing <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>12</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></math>.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;<em><strong><br>[4 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"21769","referenceCode":"21M.3.AHL.TZ1.1h.ii","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"Hence or otherwise find an equation for L in the form L(t)=p sin(qt+r)+d, where p, q, r, d∈ℝ.","paper":"3","level":"AHL","questionNumber":"h.ii","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 4]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 1—Number and algebra","Topic 1—Number and algebra","AHL 1.13—Polar and Euler form"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}}}